When two aircraft are converging at approximately the same altitude, the aircraft that has the other on its right shall give way, except as provided in **Section 1.7.3(2)** for:
- power-driven, heavier-than-air aircraft vs. airships, gliders, and balloons;
- airships vs. gliders and balloons;
- gliders vs. balloons; and
- power-driven aircraft vs. aircraft towing gliders or other objects or carrying a slung load.

Also, **Section 602.21(4)** states that an aircraft required to give way must avoid collision if there is any risk of collision.

For **night VFR flight in a power-driven aircraft**, the required equipment is listed in **Section 605.16(1)** and, where applicable, **Section 605.17**:

- **Section 605.16(1)(a) to (n)**: the equipment referred to in **paragraphs 605.14(c) to (n)**, plus:
  - **sensitive altimeter adjustable for barometric pressure**;
  - **turn and slip indicator or turn coordinator**;
  - **adequate source of electrical energy** for all electrical and radio equipment;
  - **spare fuses** equal to at least 50% of installed fuses of each rating accessible to the pilot-in-command;
  - **stabilized magnetic direction indicator or gyroscopic direction indicator** if the aerodrome is not visible from the aircraft;
  - **means of establishing direction not dependent on a magnetic source** if operated within the Northern Domestic Airspace;
  - **radiocommunication equipment** adequate for two-way communication on the appropriate frequency in **Class B, C, or D airspace**, an **MF area** (unless operating under **subsection 602.97(3)**), or the **ADIZ**;
  - **radio navigation equipment** if operated under **Subpart 4 of this Part** or **Subpart 5 of Part VII**;
  - **radio navigation equipment adequate to receive radio signals from a transmitting facility** if operated under **Subpart 4 of this Part** or **Subpart 5 of Part VII**;
  - **radio navigation equipment** where required in **Class B airspace** to operate in accordance with a flight plan.

- **Section 605.17(1)**: when operating at night, the aircraft’s **position lights and anti-collision lights must be turned on**, subject to **Section 605.17(2)**.

- **Section 605.16(1)(a)** also includes the equipment in **Section 605.14(c) to (n)**, but that section is not fully provided in the context, so I can’t list those items specifically.

If you want, I can also give you a **clean checklist version** of the night VFR equipment requirements from the provided sections.

The Canada Water Aerodrome Supplement (CWAS) contains:

- tabulated data and graphical information in support of Canadian VFR charts;
- an aerodrome/facilities directory of all water aerodromes shown on Canadian VFR charts;
- communications station data;
- radio aids; and
- other supplemental data.  

